One way to explore this is looking at how science production changes when
 lab notebooks go online or raw data is freed and subject to scrutiny.
 By both opening up with my own work and looking at larger trends of open
 science, I can get a better handle on the value of such practices.
 Essentially, I want to generate my own data in the lab and have the global
 community critique and contribute it as a means to examining open source
 science in practice, not just theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The even bigger encapsulating question around all of this is constantly
 considering the global aspects of knowledge – where, and by who, is “knowledge”
 of any kind produced and used.
 One example is the claims by open science advocates that developing countries
 need open access publications to “catch up” with the rest of us and even
 the playing field.
 But that narrative is disrupted by the actual scholars of the Global South
 -- discussions of how open access can reinforce colonial consumer-producer
 relationships [2] or how open access doesn't rectify the disparity in the
 number of peer-reviewed international journals indexed by the Thomson-Reuters
 Web of Science (4% of Latin American journals in 2012) and the consequent
 impact factor that drives the current academic system [5].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are broad questions about culture and science as a system, but my
 foray into stem cell differentiation will be done in such a way as to model
 how science can (and perhaps should) interact with the culture around it
 and start addressing those issues, both scientific and cultural.
 
